Following discussions in #4431, this PR disables OpenTK HiDPI mode.

Making MonoGame HiDPI-compliant with OpenTK doesn't look to be interesting considering that it will be replaced, so this is a quick and safe workaround.

@dellis1972 @cra0zy what do you think?

The most stripped down repro I can come up with is below. This example sets up a DepthStencilState that should only write when the stencil buffer has a 1 in it. So, since nothing at all is ever written to the stencil buffer nothing should ever be end up in the framebuffer. The actual output is that the texture is written to the framebuffer when it should not ever pass the stencil test.

``` csharp
    public class Game1 : Game
    {
        GraphicsDeviceManager graphics;
        SpriteBatch _spriteBatch;
        Texture2D _maskTex;

        // only write when the stencil buffer has 1
        public static DepthStencilState EqualStencilState = new DepthStencilState() {
            StencilEnable = true,
            StencilFunction = CompareFunction.Equal,
            StencilPass = StencilOperation.Keep,
            ReferenceStencil = 1,
            DepthBufferEnable = false,
        };


        public Game1()
        {
            graphics = new GraphicsDeviceManager( this );
            graphics.PreferredDepthStencilFormat = DepthFormat.Depth24Stencil8;
            Content.RootDirectory = "Content";              
        }


        protected override void LoadContent()
        {
            // Create a new SpriteBatch, which can be used to draw textures.
            _spriteBatch = new SpriteBatch( GraphicsDevice );
            _maskTex = Content.Load<Texture2D>( "mask" );
        }


        protected override void Draw( GameTime gameTime )
        {
            GraphicsDevice.Clear( Color.Transparent );

            _spriteBatch.Begin( SpriteSortMode.Immediate, null, SamplerState.PointClamp, EqualStencilState, null, null );
            _spriteBatch.Draw( _maskTex, new Vector2( 200, 200 ), Color.White );
            _spriteBatch.End();

            base.Draw( gameTime );
        }
    }
```

Doing some experimenting against XNA for #4425 I found that our implementation of `GraphicsDevice.PresentationParameters` is wrong.

`GraphicsDevice.PresentationParameters` is only the output presentation values representing the state of the `GraphicsDevice` the last time the presentation was changed.

This means `GraphicsDeviceManager` shouldn't be making changes to it directly.  Instead `GraphicsDeviceManager` should be creating a new `PresentationParameters` object... populating it with the new state... then passing that to `GraphicsDeviceManager` to become the new presentation state.

Some code that currently fails under MonoGame:

```
var oldpp = GraphicsDevice.PresentationParameters;
GraphicsDeviceManager.PreferredBackBufferWidth = 100;
GraphicsDeviceManager.ApplyChanges();
var newpp = GraphicsDevice.PresentationParameters; 
Debug.Assert(!object.ReferenceEquals(oldpp, newpp));
```
